{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Wealthy art collectors are benefiting from tax breaks when they build museums with limited public access, often near their homes.", "abstract": "Growing number of wealthy art collectors are establishing private tax-exempt exhibition spaces, often within a stone's throw from their homes; status allows them to deduct full market value of their artworks, and the cost of their upkeep, while retaining de facto control of the collections and limiting the volume of visitors to the space; critics worry that taxpayers are subsidizing multimillion-dollar art purchases with little public benefit in return.", "section_name": "Business Day", "print_page": null, "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Patricia", "role": "reported", "lastname": "COHEN", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By PATRICIA COHEN", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/11/business/art-collectors-gain-tax-benefits-from-private-museums.html", "lead_paragraph": "Wealthy art collectors are benefiting from tax breaks when they build museums with limited public access, often near their homes.", "headline": {"seo": "Art Collectors Gain Tax Benefits From Private Museums", "main": "Writing Off the Warhol Next Door ", "print_headline": "Writing Off the Warhol Next Door"}, "_id": "54b144b838f0d8367c8434dc", "word_count": "2582", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/01/11/business/11-MUSEUMTAX-JP2/11-MUSEUMTAX-JP2-thumbWide-v3.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/01/11/business/11-MUSEUMTAX-JP2/11-MUSEUMTAX-JP2-thumbWide-v3.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 466, "url": "images/2015/01/11/business/11-MUSEUMTAX-JP2/11-MUSEUMTAX-JP2-articleLarge-v2.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/01/11/business/11-MUSEUMTAX-JP2/11-MUSEUMTAX-JP2-articleLarge-v2.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "466"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width":